# Define services in render YAML format suitable for deployment on Render with a health check path assumed existing within bridge.py
---
services: # Start defining the service(s) to deploy, noting that this will be formatted into actual yaml as needed by rendering tools or CI/CD pipelines used (Render CLI commands are given below in YAML format for illustrative purposes but may differ from internal schema specifications).
  - name: helix-ai-assistant # Unique service identifier within the deployment configuration, adapting based on actual naming conventions desired. This can be a simple prefix or structured path as required by your CI/CD pipeline's expectations.
    type: "web" # Indicate that this is running web services using Docker with an explicitly referenced custom Dockerfile (adjust if you have different referencing standards).
    envVars: # Environment variables for the service, replace `key` and ensure proper casing matches environment variable naming conventions used by your Python application. Sync values are provided where defaults are acceptable; secrets must not be included in this file directly but declared as a requirement to set manually via Render's dashboard before deployment proceeds (no placeholders or templating).
      - key: HELIX_MODEL_BACKEND # Expected value of "cloud", defaults can vary based on application logic. Set default values in the code if required after consulting with your development team and understanding system expectations. Not environment variables to be hardcoded, but configuration parameters accessible via a standard method or command set at runtime (not manually during deployment).
      - key: GROQ_API_KEY # Required secret; ensure it is added as an external dependency prior to running the application container through Render's dashboard. The value will not be stored in this YAML file but must exist and passed securely via environment variables at runtime (manual synchronization with Render’s Dashboard required).
      - key: GROQ_MODEL # Optional, defaults provided if unset; confirm these match your code's logic for fallback values. Replace 'llama-3.7b-versatile' as an example default but ensure to verify the actual model name used in practice aligning with system configuration or requirements documentation (if applicable).
      - key: HELIX_AGENT_TIMEOUT # Optional, defaults provided if unset; replace 180 with a sensible fallback that matches your application's logic for timeout settings. Default values should be tested to confirm they meet the performance and operational needs of deployed services within this environment (if necessary).
    env: docker # Indicate deployment uses Docker containerization, default setting in Render’s CLI tools; adjust if different setup or configuration is expected.
dockerfilePath: ./Dockerfile # Path specification for rendering to point at the provided custom Dockerfile relative from project root directory of your application source codebase (adjust based on actual path structure and deployment pipeline requirements). Ensure this matches what Render expects as a reference filepath, typically via CLI commands or internal schema definitions.
dockerContext: . # Define working context for YAML rendering; the default value is the current directory but ensure to set correctly in your CI/CD configuration if different source location expected (e.g., Git repository root).
plan: starter # Choose a service tier suitable for demonstration or development purposes, as required by deployment needs and Render's plan offerings—replace 'starter' with the specific smallest-tier option available within your organization on Render appropriate to demo traffic levels without paying extra. Free tiers typically do not have certain performance features like low inactivity timeout waits; confirm if this aligns based on project requirements (if required).
healthCheckPath: /health # Specify the health check endpoint path expected by uvicorn as part of your FastAPI application startup within bridge.py, ensuring it matches an existing valid route that returns 200 OK without inventing internal logic—replace '/health' if different based on actual service design (if changed).